        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Just to be clearer, here's my issue:\r\n\r\n1. Someone reads CHANGES.rst and finds out about `CYTHON_LIMITED_API`\r\n2. They read about the benefits of `Py_LIMITED_API` and think \"oh, this would be great, I should turn on `CYTHON_LIMITED_API`!\"\r\n3. They try running Cython and compiling with `-DCYTHON_LIMITED_API=1`\r\n4. Their code builds and run, and so they think \"ah, excellent, my code works with `Py_LIMITED_API`!\"\r\n\r\nHowever, this has only worked because `CYTHON_LIMITED_API` doesn't actually enable `Py_LIMITED_API`, despite what is currently in CHANGES.rst.\r\n\r\nI just think that the current content is misleading to the current status of things: \"many features do not yet work\" suggests that Cython or the compilation is likely to fall-over if you try running with it (therefore it is \"obvious\" if your code doesn't work with `Py_LIMITED_API`) -- however, actually, enabling `CYTHON_LIMITED_API` doesn't actually enable `Py_LIMITED_API`, so you don't know if your code works with the limited API or not.\r\n\r\n(I should say: I'm not a user of this functionality, I just came across this while trying to resolve #4111, and thought it was worth writing up that it feels misleading -- apologies if it seems I've been \"overly negative\" about `CYTHON_LIMITED_API`)",
